messages.content: my understanding of ultra lag and why it happens:

The position of an object is constantly updated while you're holding it. But if you store the object and leave the area while it's stored, the position can no longer be updated. As a result, the position changes create some sort of stack in the memory which - combined with the graphics on screen - slows down the game. When you go back to the storage area, the position changes are applied, but there are so many that the game freezes for a while. The framerate goes back to normal once the changes are cleared.
I still don't know why ambient lag affects it, but I think that shed some light on it
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-1LN_Cqlboc

By performing "Barrel Storage" on a Hunky Chunky Barrel (and presumably other transformation barrels) you have a single frame to pull out an invisible version of your character's gun. It can be fired and you can pivot while holding Z, but you lose it the moment you move or jump. You can also use your instrument and cause the camera to behave oddly during this time.

[old] Whenever you pause exit, die, or void out, all temporary flags from the current level (such as oranges, ammo crates, and uncollected GBs from bonus barrels) will be reset. This also gets rid of flashback warp and cutscene storage. The same thing happens if you leave any level through the DK portal.
Exceptions are green cells in this spreadsheet: https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1osCrSGC6qz0TybcPFlt4H39wPy1_aeRwJz0hadEQmS8/edit#gid=176739036

embeds.title: DK64 - Bone displacement bug
embeds.description: DK64 - Bone displacement bug What is it? Most animated 3D models in DK64 are composed of structures called bones which group many vertices together. This makes animation much easier by allowing the artist to update the position of a single bone and have all associated vertices move relative to that

messages.content:
I made some progress with our understanding of ultralag today.
DK64 has a massive linked list which spans most of the N64 memory, I like to call it the "backbone".
Ordinarily the backbone contains around 1,000-2,000 objects of varying sizes.
During ultralag however it contains over 20,000 objects mostly of size 0x20, 0x10 and 0.
I had a look at the size 0x20 objects and they seemed like another linked list of sorts, eventually leading to an 0x20 sized object pointed to by the boulder object directly.
The pointer is located at boulder + 0x13C. This is the same pointer that locks the kongs controls during enemy knockback, during cutscenes and when entering a tag barrel.
When the player enters the chunk that the boulder was originally stored in, the game frees the memory used by all of these objects, bringing the backbone back down to ~1500 objects.
Interestingly if I freeze boulder + 0x13C to 0x00000000 I can enter the chunk that the boulder was stored in without the objects being freed, thus keeping ultralag effects.
pretty interesting research there 😛
So we're not duping the boulder as such, but we definitely are duping something

small tidbit on swimming+skew: When underwater, the entire kong model rotates forward rather but the axes stay stationary. So for example, the x-axis is always forwards backwards, y is updown, and z is side to side. Therefore the rotations are defined by the right hand rule where your thumb sits on that axis. Standing rotations about x keep your front facing forward however you lay on your sides, rotations about y is what is allowed in game by crouch turning, and rotations about z are the usual skew.

When swimming, the model lies forward but those axes are still in those directions: rotations about x make the kong "corkscrew" (not a barrel roll you plebs) while still facing forward (btw you also automatically correct to standard rotation slowly). Rotations in y keep the kong's front facing downwards and rotations in z are what we are allowed when we hold Z for braking (hence why skew works).
this is likely all understood basically but just wanted to write down exactly how it worked if it had never been done

For reference, what "RingRush's setup is"
1. Pick a place in front of b locker, I personally like the right half but I don't think it needs to be there. Some places might be more lenient than others but idk yet
2. Backflip until you get the "land and immediately fall" animation.
3. Do minimal movement backflips (1 frame at something like 1/3 forward) to move .2 units at a time, until you get the land and fall animation again.
4. Jump and push back a bit in midair to test if you clipped
5. If you didn't, repeat steps 3 and 4.

When you get the quick fall off you are being placed at high 383 or low 384 X position (I'm assuming mid-right side of b locker...the exact X coordinates change as you move left and right). The gap is .028 units wide (at the place I tested, may be different in other places?). Your goal upon sliding off is to land a multiple of .2 from the gap. Where exactly you land seems essentially random, so you have about a 1 in 7 chance of landing in a spot such that 1-4 min-move backflips get you in the gap. All you need to is keeping looping through until you hit it.

There is a ton of skill involved in hitting consistent min-move backflips. Also, jump testing without getting pushed out and having to re-enter the loop from afar can be tricky if you aren't focused.

Overall, I think getting this trick within a minute on average is reasonable assuming you master these super small movements

- Having the Arcade Room not loaded upon completing Arcade Round 1 delays the GB cutscene. This delay also persists through voids
- Entering T&S During the GB Cutscene, then exiting causes the GB to repeat it's movement towards the arcade lever
- Entering a T&S Portal as soon as the DK Arcade Intro CS plays will play the T&S Exit CS a few seconds after you're warped back into the Frantic Factory map. If you do this, you will have control of the kong whilst the GB is moving.
- If you exit the Power Shed whilst the monkey success sound is being made (tight timing), you will delay the production Room GB Cutscene, if you re-enter. You'll be able to gain control of the kong during the 'online checking' mini cutscene. This will start a small timer which counts down whilst you're in power shed. If you exit before this timer is up, you can pause it until you re-enter. The computer will re-start it's mini-cutscene, however, it'll be cut short because of the timer. Once the timer reaches 0, the Production Room on CS will play.

The death during Diddy phase takes priority over the Round Completion. In other words, if you get hit by K Rool's glove after the final switch has been hit (even if the light is lowering), you'll still die and be kicked out of the K Rool fight. On top of this, the light will disappear and will not land on K Rool. To add more to that, if you die outside the ring, you'll be warped to the centre during the death Cutscene
Also, your stored position updates when the Cutscene starts

hitting toes earlier or later on non-terminal hits does not seem to make the next round start any sooner or later. This is based on frame-by-frame emu testing which bizhawk is notoriously low lag in tiny's phase - so lag doesn't factor into this calculation.

terminal hits timing definitely matters. There is a delicate science to getting these hits as early as possible and avoiding the hurtboxes, so I can't say 100% for sure if I'm being optimal. However, I've been able to do just as well with bow shots as orange shots in hitting ASAP (in fact, bow slightly faster since the orange creates a bit of lag...but getting a perfect bow shot past a hitbox is very precise).

K rool's toe patterns are not constant and can change depending on where you are after previous attacks (from where I'm testing its single toe strikes). Some attacks seem to target where you are standing. This can actually be used to trigger the phenomena where no toe moves, if you stand on the far left of the shoe running into the wall. The no toe effect does not seem to save any time, unless it reduces lag.

On PAL, the K Rool IGT timer starts at 2:30 rather than 3:00 (Possibly to compensate for the additional lag). That being said, the text at the start of K Rool from 'Microbuffer' remains unchanged (He still calls the match "Twelve Three-Minute Rounds")

I assume that this would also trigger the theoretical quick kill if the rocket was available in an earlier phase

In short (All using tools on BizHawk w/ ScriptHawk, but thought it was noteworthy enough should we ever have the capability to pick K Rool up/Move Chunky from his initial spot in the Punch scene):

DK - You can somehow make DK Invincible to all attacks. He does the damage animation, but does not actually take any damage or die (regardless of how many times you hit him). On top of that, you can get an instant shot on K Rool if you enter the Barrel from above in a certain way when K Rool is positioned like this, and the barrel remains if you want to fire again at K Rool.
Also, as much as this seems pointless to state, the fight ends after 4 hits (Not at all tied to how many barrels are in the ring)

LANKY - Can prematurely cause the Instrument Pad spawning CS (99% sure this would be known by someone). You can get K Rool stuck in an infinite running loop and he will always want to return to that spot for some reason. However, he is in a defeatable state if you place the peels well

CHUNKY - You can get a quicker activation of the punch CS if Chunky is towards K Rool's starting position (Somehow it activtes just by charging up the PPunch).

Also, The Diddy Rocketbarrel actor (presumably from Diddy Phase) is in Chunky Phase. Potentially suggesting that they cloned the Diddy Phase map for Chunky Phase

messages.content: you can do more take picture mode glitch in other places like fungi, Aztec,Factory, and caves. AZTEC- you take the big boulder and put it right where the hunky chunky barrel is and do skid jump and quickly take your camera and take a picture before you enter the barrel. LLAMA TEMPLE- you do ledge clip and skid jump and pull up your camera and take a picture before you land in the mini monkey barrel in the fairy room its very difficult than the chunky one. FACTORY you go to the toy monster room and defeat the enemies and wait until the barrel appears,enter the barrel and detransform and stay where you are and pull out your camera and take a picture before you enter the barrel. you can also do it before the toy monster making cutscene, you can do it in 101% run if you want cause the toy monster can't hit you anymore . if you don't do it before  the cutscene starts and do the glitch the camera will follow you for the rest of the fight, you can also use that for navigating through the level if you escape the room. FUNGI- you do the same thing just like in llama temple, go to the barn area,climb a pole and skid jump and take a picture before you land in the barrel. CAVES you do the same thing just like in aztec.
if you fall into the pit you still die

Even more Take Picture Mode or Take Picture Interruption glitch ISLES- Activate TBS, setup a stored position at the hunky chunky island, the reason why you need to set a stored position there is because you can't bring the boulder to the island if you do the dry storage and go to the island the boulder will be invisible, if you put it down and go where you setup a dry storage the boulder will blow up,same if you do it at BFI, pick up a boulder,put the boulder at the hunky chunky barrel, transform into hunky chunky , stand on the boulder, detransform and take your camera out and take a picture. if you take a picture at the fairy before you enter the barrel it doesn't refill your stuff so the fairy is saved right when you start the glitch. FUNGI- better method bring your steel keg outside, put the steel keg at the mini monkey barrel, tag tiny, transform and detransform and take your camera out and take a picture before you enter the barrel.

messages.content: This is a way to do Mech Fish without having to worry about doing the "shoot two targets within 7 frames of each other" setup

I used a combination of Ringrush's LOTAD video to determine the "shoot a target within 7 frame of it starting/stopping", along with my conclusion of shooting when the timer turns to 91 for the 2nd target, along with GloriousLiar's find of throwing oranges at the bottom target. This gets you a 75-76 everytime if you shoot the top two targets optimally.
If you do fail shooting out both targets on the top, you can just wait for it to cycle back around after you throw oranges at the bottom target, but it will cost you two cycles.

Reminder that 75-76 doing it this way is better than the old 78-80 because we shoot the bottom target on the first cycle it is available. You could still get a 78-80 by doing the original doubleshot setup, which would be the optimal way to do it RTA.
NOTE: This way only tested on VC. I believe the timer still works the same way on N64, as I believe some(?) runners were doing this.
Also should note, doing the cutscene skip on the BoM Off Cutscene won't open the K Rool door. You have to reset (Exiting/Entering your file presumably works too) in order to open it

messages.content:
So Model 1 Object + 0x144 is the "noclip bitfield".
Common values are 00111100 (0x3C, normal) and 00000001 (0x01, noclip), however, any value without both of these bits set: 00001100 will allow the object to clip through walls.
The game sets the value to 0x01 in the following situations:
- Using Bananaporter
- Using Monkeyport Pad
- Using Battle Crown pad
- Using Baboon Blast pad
- Entering Tag Barrel
- Entering Rambi/Enguarde Crate
- Entering Kong Specific Barrel (except Rocketbarrel)
- Playing Instrument (except in Lanky phase)
- Falling in lava during Dogadon fights
- Loss dance
- Searchlight Seek
- Possibly more...?
Cancelling one of those actions before they end will preserve the value 0x01, eg. Galleon Bananaporter Noclip.
Allowing an animation to end on/in water seems to preserve the value 0x01.
Allowing an animation to end on land (eg. rolling, jumping, attacking) will reset the value to 0x3C.
I have added this value to ScriptHawk's OSD and a checkbox which sets the value to 0x01 to the options form.

You can get DK Portal Storage in Galleon with the Cannon Room gate opening cutscene. In most situations, this is either immediately activated before the cutscene (If you enter the portal zone before the camera changes to view the gate opening), or after the cutscene (If you enter the portal zone during the camera being locked on the gate). However, if you were out of portal range when the cutscene ends, you'd store the DK Portal until the DK Portal reloads.

In general there seems to be 2 methods:

- Get something which locks the camera and results in a DK/T&S Portal being deloaded (Eg. Cannon Game/Cannon Gate Cutscene). Enter the portal zone during this.

- Start the portal animation, but interrupt it with something which has higher priority than the portal animation that deloads the portal (eg. Entering Arcade with Lever Storage/Activating the Chunky 'Help Me' Cutscene).

To preserve the storage, just ensure that the portal is deloaded as soon as the camera locks onto the kong again.

Being in the portal exit animation upon collecting a GB will skip the dance.
The current only way to get this RTA would be to pick up the rock with a GB inside, and throw the rock so the GB is in front of a Troff 'n' Scoff Portal. Then enter that Troff 'n' Scoff portal with a non-Chunky kong, then tag Chunky inside T&S and exit the portal.

The portal Entrance animation also works in the same way. Just enter the portal with Chunky when the GB is bouncing.

If you place a boulder under a barrel, and then throw the GB Rock so the GB lands on that boulder, you can get it so the Barrel animation also skips the GB dance

You can also get temporary portal skew from the portal entrance animation and the GB too. However, the timing is very tight, and as before, you'll be taken to T&S before you gain control http://i.imgur.com/cDwBLQS.png

On top of this, entering Bonus Barrels removes the boulder with the banana bunch in it. So if you place a GB which normally obeys gravity (Eg. the Rock GB) on top of the banana bunch boulder and then enter a bonus barrel; when you return to the main map, the GB will float even though it's meant to obey gravity. http://i.imgur.com/cBbGFTk.png

messages.content: To expand on what Adam said, coins are stored as an 8-bit integer so it does mod 256 when it saves; 999 mod 256 = 231, 1014 mod 256 = 246. If you were to get up to 1024 coins you'd have 0 on reset

- Get TBS on Barrel near Tree (Either with Diddy, or another kong and tag Diddy later)
- Wake Owl, Enter Rocketbarrel, Start Race
- Race to W4, Head to the Rocketbarrel near the Clock, Shoot the Day Switch to get the FTT just at the right time so the cutscene will play whilst the 'Try again' is on screen
- Retry Race, and quickly head to within the Tree Tag Barrel range so you get another Kong in Rocketbarrel (which will autofail the race and pull up the try again prompt)
- Don't restart race, pause
- Tada

When you're on a slippery slope and start the sliding animation, if you jump (you can aerial as well to make it easier) then land back on the slope while holding Z, you will not re-enter the sliding animation and will be crouched going down the slope. You can do Z+button moves while in this state. Rolling and chimpy charges will not move you. If you slide off the slope you will stay crouched and can conserve some momentum, even in a direction different from the slope (ex. sliding off the front of dk isles, you can move toward the training ground entrance and long jump into it.) If you're in this state and take out your camera before landing on another slope, you won't be kicked out of it and will stay on the slope until you exit first-person (you cannot put the camera away or switch to your gun, and you have to be in the air to take out your camera.)

Unrelated to this if you're in the water and take a picture, then have your kong land on the ground during the animation, you will regain control (this can be done on top of the chest in galleon.) You can also regain control if you take a picture before hitting a slope (not using the mechanic in the last message.)

With usage of Shrunky Kong (might not be required, not tested), you can get below the floor in Isles T&S on VC (Around y=-50. For reference, the normal floor is around y=10, and the first step at either side is around y=40)

Method (Will get a video at some point within the next week if it becomes noteworthy):
- ISG, Isles Snide's Fadeout, Watch rest of intro story, head to Aztec
- Get Shrunky Kong

- Navigate to the left side regular void wall
- Head up until you're in line with near to where the boss door tunnel visually ends (This should be somewhat close to the rear void)
- Navigate towards the boss door tunnel
- Jump aerial towards the boss door, and then head backwards mid jump. This is where you should lose height

Just so that this is in doc:

If you wait an extremely long time (over 12800 years), the timestamp used to calculate the ISG timer will overflow back to 0. As a result, you can skip the 4:26 fadeout (assuming you never activated it) and go back to 0:00.

In theory, if you picked up key 8 too late when doing 2015 route, you could wait 12,800+ years and then pause quit to skip prematurely fading out.
Obviously this isn't gonna be useful RTA.

Unfortunately the ISG timer is reset before you gain control in DK's house, meaning that stuff like double FBW (w/ ISG) are not currently possible

Optimisation documentation [Maybe known]:
**Number 1**
Vertical Acceleration is slower in rocketbarrel when holding A **and** either up or down on the stick. Once you reach terminal vertical velocity, holding up/down/neutral doesn't affect your vertical speed at that point or in the future.

For example: If you're trying to go up a lot and then a little forward (eg. In NLE when you go from the Rocketbarrel in Castle near Tiny's BP to Snide's), it's better to hold A and not move the stick until you reach terminal vertical velocity, at which point, then move the the stick upwards (whilst still holding A) so that you get closer to Snide's horizontally

Data:
   No Direction
   Y = -103.48 (F = 11981)
   Y = 405.116 (F = 12164)
   dY = 508.596, dF = 183. dY/dF = 2.779

   Direction
   Y = -103.48 (F = 11981)
   Y = 436.134 (F = 12392)
   dY = 539.614, dF = 411. dY/dF = 1.313

**Number 2**
The same effect applies to if you are falling with rocketbarrel and want to stop mid-air. Holding A & up/down will mean that your vertical slowdown takes significantly longer than if you didn't hold up/down.

**Number 3**
When falling, if you want to stop mid-air, it doesn't matter whether you hold A (to go back up) or hold Z (to maintain rocketbarrel elevation), your slowdown will take the exact same time AS long as you are not holding anything on the stick if you use A

messages.content:
Depending on the height at which you fire out of a Cannon Barrel at (in DK Phase), your landing position after hitting K Rool differs. As a result, this can alter you being closer or further away from the next Cannon Barrel.

List of heights at which you fire at (with the frame difference between the first successful frame you can fire at when the barrel is on it's way down) [Blue Columns] and where you land relative to the next barrel [Grey Column]. It won't save any frames to not fire at the first frame, but it *may* not lose any frames to fire on the second, depending on certain factors

For clarification:
140 Sp. = Speed of DK Walking and the very end of his roll
250 Sp. = Peak speed of DK's Roll

Phasewalk with easier inputs (though not as high velocity so may not work on some off-angle walls that the normal method can):
1. Get as close to a wall as possible (i.e. jump backwards with DK)
2. Face the wall and enter first person + pull out your gun
(Standard phasewalk: next steps happen on consecutive frames)
3. Exit first person with a neutral stick
4. Press back slightly (or fully) (or another direction as long as it moves DK away from the wall)
5. Neutral stick
(Change)
6. Press and hold forward + Z. Return to neutral  within ~0.3 seconds for more consistent results.

This has the benefit of skipping the 1 frame return to neutral after the forward press. Downside is angles need to be a bit better to clip because of the lower speed, and it requires gun.

As a pointless aside the gun slide state that results from this maintains phase capabilities as long as you don't change your angle. You can't move other than the initial slide like this, but it does has some weird side effects. For instance, if you fire a bullet it will quickly blow up.

messages.content:
If you press B during the first 2 frames of Diddy being grounded (Y Value being the same as the floor value) with the stick being held up after Diddy lands from an aerial attack, he preserves 150 speed during the entire resulting cartwheel (normally 140 speed).

On top of this, if you jump out of your 150-speed-cartwheel and then press A on the 2nd frame diddy is grounded (1st would produce a 120-speed double jump), Diddy's resulting jump would be 150 speed (normally 140 speed). These can be chained together for infinite 150-speed-jumps.

Obviously the cartwheel 150-speed preservation is easier because of a 2-frame window. However, with either of these techniques, Diddy's optimal movement speed will always be  the 1 frame of 140 speed to start the first cartwheel and then 150 speed throughout until you break the cartwheel + jump + aerial chain (or jump chain).

You can change directions with this without losing speed, but you have to hold up for the 1st frame of a cartwheel (or whatever direction you were moving) to initiate a 150-speed cartwheel, and then change directions to whatever way you are wanting to move on subsequent frames

With this, average kong speed leaderboard:
1) **DK** - 192.92 (Roll with neutral input to slow decelleration)
2) **Diddy** - 150 (Cartwheel & jump aerial chains, asymptotes at 150 the longer the chain)
3) **Tiny** - 149.46 (Long Jump & moving attack cancel)
4) **Lanky** - 149.45 (Long Jump & moving attack cancel)
5) **Chunky** - 149.43 (Long Jump & moving attack cancel)

Movement optimisation tech (Maybe RTA viable?), when climbing a pole that auto-takes you off when you climb to the top: The frame before you auto-jump off (The frame before your horizontal veloc is set to 200), set your input to neutral.
Rather than your veloc going straight from 200 > 140, you decelerate at a rate of -4 units per second (from 200), obviously saving time

**Optimisation**
- Crouch & Orangstand
- Jump ASAP. Optimal is frame after you press B, but the frame window for getting 170 speed is really big
- Make sure A is held for as long as possible
- Have neutral held to slow deceleration on landing, keep Z held for a couple frames until 140 speed is hit (2 frames of neutral & Z). This prevents the velocity dipping below 140 during the uncrouch

- Re-hold Z during the uncrouch to buffer the crouch

There is a small gap between when the flag is saved and when the integer related to the collectable is updated. If you pause, manual save and reset during this gap, you can set the flag without updating the integer. As such, you "delete" the collectable.

This applies to:
- Golden Bananas
- Banana Coins
- Coloured Bananas (Bunches, Singles & Balloons)

The totals for other major collectables are based off the flags directly (eg. the game sums the amount of keys acquired flags that are set to total up the amount of keys you have)

As such, it is (in theory) possible to "collect" everything in the game and only get 13% on the file (10 Crowns, 8 Keys, 20 Fairies, 2 Company Coins, the 5 Medals from Helm). There are a few Golden Bananas which lock you into collection (The 3 minecart minigames come to mind), so you can't perform this on those, but should skips on those become possible, 13%-Get everything becomes possible.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZXF920n7QJg&feature=youtu.be

messages.content:
**"Ground Effect" Explanation (AKA why does Warp 1 in Factory tag when I'm 900ft off the ground)**
In order for the "Ground Effect" to take place, 2 conditions have to be met:
1) You have to be considered grounded 1 frame before condition 2 is met (Technical definition of "grounded" is at the bottom)

2) The vertical gap between the kong and the object you are trying to activate by using the ground effect cannot have a floor between it (Otherwise the ground effect will take place on that floor instead)

The ground effect when falling off a platform is only active for 1 frame.

From what I can tell, this only works for solid objects which a kong can stand on (AKA slam pads, crown pads, warp pads work. Golden Bananas, cutscene triggers and other miscellaneous collectables do not).

As such, it is possible to Slam a pad from off the ground: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PXEaSvi9CXw&feature=youtu.be

**Technical definition of "grounded"** - The final bit in the 1-byte bitfield that is located 0x6B into the player object has to be set to 1. Essentially this is a boolean value which determines whether the player is grounded (1) or not (0). Forcing this bit to be 1 with emulation tools means you can get the ground effect automatically. Just because a kong visually doesn't look grounded doesn't mean they aren't actually grounded (Simian Slamming being a perfect example)

messages.content:
0x80752c70 is a function pointer list (swimming, climb tree, swing on vine)
0x807fc924 is a pointer to the Action object (?)
-> offset 0x29c is the action initiated field
so if you dereference the action object, set the object initiated field to a byte 0x00 - 0x5C, the kong function wrapper (at 0x806eb194) will execute the code at 0x80752c70 + action * 4 (indexing the function list)

some of these functions are known, some need to be filled out

the take me there code takes advantage of this by:
getting the action object pointer from 0x807fc924
dereferencing that address to get the action object (tentative name)
setting the address of the action object, offset by 0x29c to 0x3B
0x3B jumps to a function at 0x80752c70 +4*0x3b = some state change/tagging function
(cross referenced this with a doc of actions that ballam has been keeping and verified independently)
https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1zzIjucMRbeLMwqgK4C1CbVrDfMbLLwe8bQLAzHsTR6Y/edit?usp=sharing

messages.content: SP of on Kroc Arm & 0,0,0
Explanation: The Kroc Arm floor (1620) is being persisted despite the game trying to warp you to 0,0,0

So it warps you to 0,0,0, but because the floor value of 1620 is maintained, it warps you up to 0,1620,0. Hence why the floor is also maintained. Intended Lateral location (In this case X=0, Z=0) has to be out of bounds so that the floor value isn't altered after it's set to that high value
This does the same thing when you climb a swinging vine

messages.content:
> - If you enter the mini monkey barrel in the last second (?) you will transform into mini monkey after the detrans trigger allowing you to be mini monkey when you shouldn't be. Using the FTT Textboxes means K Rool won't spawn any shockwaves whilst the textbox is active
> - First timeout immediately clears any toe progress, so you can't beat the round with this
> - If you don't have the Cranky K Rool Temp Flag set (0xB,3), the Cranky cutscene will auto-pull up after the stuff in the toe
> - The cranky cutscene itself doesn't reset anything about the phase (phase timer, toe progress) or advance the round counter at all (sadly)
> - Since the first toe completion temp flag is set, K Rool will be in the damaged state when you pull into Tiny Phase again, but as soon as the timer becomes active again, since it wasn't reset to 3:00.00, you'll time out again (for real this time)

For some reason, the round counter gets reduced by 1 during the Cranky cutscene. If you were to enter Tiny Phase on Round 1, this would mean that Round 0 (famous for this glitch: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jkfsS2pdUeI&feature=youtu.be) is accessible for that short period of time before the 2nd timeout

You can get 13 rounds of K Rool (You get round 12 twice) with the following steps:
> - Beat Tiny Phase to set the final toe temporary flag
> - Void out in Chunky phase to prevent the round count resetting
> - Go from Helm to DK Phase
> - Void out in DK Phase so that you are DK Phase on Round 10 without watching the Cranky K Rool Cutscene
> - Beat Lanky Phase on Round 12
> - Normally the game goes to the "K Rool Victorious" cutscene when trying to load a round higher than round 12, but the tiny phase death cutscene and the option to go to the cranky cutscene makes the game go to the Cranky cutscene
> - The Cranky Cutscene reduces the round to round 11
> - Going back into Tiny Phase will auto-beat it and mean you get to Chunky Phase on Round 12

messages.content:
A while back @zorulda found a weird glitch where he seemed to be warped out of bounds after throwing a cannonball in Galleon, which can be seen here: https://www.twitch.tv/zorulda/clip/BlushingCarelessMonitor4Head?filter=clips&range=all&sort=time
After a bit of debugging, I have come up with the following circumstances needed for this to work:
> The base idea is being in the area of the cannonball the frame before it's respawned or the frame it has been respawned. These are the only two frames the warp can work

> The "won't respawn" sphere around the cannonball has a radius of 50 units (for reference, at peak lagless speed, DK moves 6.25 units in 1 frame). As long as you are in this area, the cannonball won't respawn. The area where you will get a warp is approximately a cylinder with radius of 10 units, and height of 20 units. To summarise, you need to be out of the 50 unit range of the cannonball for it to respawn and then within the next 2 frames, you need to be in the warp cylinder

> The warp itself moves you about 450 units and always seems to move you to around 1700, y, 2400)

> This should be easier on PAL due to the 1.2x scale up of movement

Confirmation on BizHawk: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QBGJmrkLVJ0&feature=youtu.be

Super theoretical and totally not viable strat to skip Arcade in a file for Nintendo Coin (Requires doing Arcade in another file).
**Doesn't work as of yet, but putting it here for those who might have ideas to solve the problem**:
> Have save data for more than 1 file. 1 file needs to have:
> - Arcade Lever Spawned
> - High W4 in Isles Tagged
> - Factory opening cutscenes cleared
> - Key 3 not acquired
> - Arcade R1 GB acquired
> The other file can have anything on it (except Nintendo Coin because that would defeat the purpose of this glitch)

**Steps**
> Story Skip, ISG, Enter file with the above list of requirements
> 
> W4, Enter Factory, Head to Arcade Room (You tend to get there around 1:30ish on the ISG timer)
> 
> Store Arcade lever, enter T&S to cancel fadeout, tag Lanky or Tiny
> 
> Cancel fadeout exiting T&S, move to a place where Arcade area isn't loaded.
> 
> Reactivate lever with instrument play in that place, complete 2nd round of Arcade. This sets a temporary flag that tells the game to spawn Nintendo Coin as soon as the Arcade area is reloaded.
> 
> Change the focused file to the other file mentioned above without going into DKTV (This is where the problem lies).
> 
> ISG Fadeout into new file, head to factory in new file to activate Nintendo Coin acquisition cutscene.

Currently the closest thing we have is waiting for the intro timer to overflow (Takes 12808 Years) and then quitting the game. This puts us in the right file, but in a game mode where you cannot move.

In short, the missing piece is transitioning from in factory in one file to another file without going through DKTV, but in a game mode where you have control

UPDATE - Solved: https://twitter.com/tjballaam/status/1260681652206030851

messages.content: Minor movement optimisation: When pulling out a gun in 3rd person, you end the animation 2 frames sooner with a non-neutral stick

How to get a gun slide (See https://pastebin.com/iVx9eA6A for demos of this):
> Pull out a gun in 3rd person with a non-neutral stick

> 2 frames before the premature ending (see previous #doc post), release the stick so it's in it's neutral position. Hold A for 3 frames
> **UPDATE: Releasing stick to neutral isn't needed**

> On the 3rd frame, press B. This will trick the game into thinking the kong is jumping when in fact they're not.

Here is why you can't do any normal actions out of this
> Because the game considers you jumping, you can't do a jump out of a gun slide. Weirdly, Diddy cannot double jump even though he's considered grounded

> Since you have the gun out, the gun overrides the B move. So you can't aerial/ground attack. You are also too close to the ground to aerial

> Since you are too close the ground, you also cannot simian slam

> Since you are jumping, you can't use any ground pads (Monkeyport, Warp pads, Sim Spring etc.)
This is probably already known https://youtu.be/cIPa6X1LB_c

messages.content:
Momentum Conservation Trick (Only really relevant for TAS)
> **Description**
```
If you are in TBS (entering TBS as DK) and are rolling at the point you get to your desired kong, if you press B to tag a kong during the slowdown phase of the roll, you will get a slower deceleration rate (-7u/f compared to -20u/f normally).

With this, you can boost your avg speed for that roll to 206.58 (vs 192.92 normally)
```

> **Versions this works on**
🇺🇸 🇪🇺 🇯🇵

Moonkick rolls:
> **Description**
```
Moonkick Rolls (Initiating a moonkick, then starting a roll as soon as you land) are ever so slightly faster than plain rolling depending on the difference between the start Y value and the destination Y value. This is quite situation-specific, so I don't think this will be something worth considering for RTA unless the moonkick has a large amount of frame leniency.

For Example, if the Y difference is 0 (AKA the ground where you where you land from the moonkick is no higher or lower than the Y value of the ground at the start of your kick), here is how things stack up:
Moonkick: 188.82
Roll: 192.92
Moonkick Roll: 193.02
(Speed is measured irrespective of size or lag. Kongs walk at 140 speed)

As the destination ground gets lower relative to your starting ground (negative Y difference), the moonkick & moonkick roll get faster on average. The bounds of where certain movement methods become the fastest:
Rolling is fastest: Y Difference > 9.5
Moonkick Roll is fastest: Y Difference <= 9.5
Moonkick faster than rolling: Y Difference < -382.5
Moonkick is fastest: Never (Unless a roll cannot be fitted in, in which case, see previous item)

(Y Difference is measured in units, where each kong walks at 3.5 units per 1/30th second. Moonkick/Moonkick Roll asymptote at 200 speed)
```

> **Versions this works on**
🇺🇸 🇯🇵 (Probably 🇪🇺  too)

messages.content:
File Percentage Mystery:
> In short, all of the multipliers listed on the DK64 Wiki are correct (No surprises): https://dk64.fandom.com/wiki/Game_Percentage

> If a file has 201 bananas, it subtracts 0.4 from the percentage.

> If a file has 100% exactly (after taking away the 0.4) and Rareware GB, it adds 1 to the percentage (as previously deduced by Connor75)

> UpdateCollectableCounts() has nothing interesting in it. No potential for a key 9 or a 21st fairy being saved to the file

Outcome result is converted into a 8-bit signed integer (Whole numbers between -128 > 127, inclusive). As such, see above/the code for conditions for the file screen to read "101%" for the 101% rules

messages.content:
Isles T&S N64 Crash explained:
> During the process of a frame, the game tries to go through the Object Model 2 list (A set of objects that are loaded as soon as a map loads) and executes some code that is stored inside the object. This code tends to be specific to each instance of the object, for example, the coconut switches in Jungle Japes would tell the game to free diddy if all 3 are activated. The code in question which first causes the crash is the pad underneath Scoff (The blue hippo)

> The game tries to calculate how high Scoff's pad should be off the ground. The way the game does this is to multiply a constant by the ratio of the amount of coloured bananas turned in vs. the amount of coloured bananas required to open the door. For example, in Jungle Japes, if you have 15 Coloured Bananas turned into Troff & Scoff, where the game wants 60 to grant access to Army Dillo, that would mean that the game would reduce the height of the pad to 1/4 of it's maximum (1/4 being derived by 15 / 60)

> So the game grabs the world of the parent map (Eg. If you entered the T&S in the Crypt in Castle, it grabs the overall world as "Castle"). For Isles T&S, this world is grabbed as Isles (world index 7). When you look in the array for the total CBs required, it indicates 0 CBs needed to open the door. As such, when performing this arithmetic, the game tries to do 0 / 0. Anything divided by 0 is a problem, but the game initially is okay with this as it has a failsafe to prevent some divide by 0 crashes.
> However, shortly after this division, the game converts the outcome of that division into a different format (Specifically a single-precision float into a double-precision float). There is no failsafe for this, which is what causes the crash.

> Now, some may be asking why Helm T&S doesn't crash since the boss door says that 0 CBs are needed to open it. Well, stored *right* after the CB requirement array is the B. Locker requirement array. Helm is level index 8, so it reads the first entry in the B.; Locker Requirement array (1 GB for Jungle Japes), and so references this as the denominator for the division (eg. 0 / 1). Therefore, this results in the operation being 0 and doesn't crash

> As to why VC doesn't crash, it's assumed that it's something to do with the compiler used in the Wii U Virtual console. However, at this point.... who knows.
> *(It's unknown whether this is the cause of the corrupt geometry in VC Isles T&S)*

> Since all this happens before you have control, and the arrays are constants that are never overwritten, and the code for each of the Objects in the subset are run regardless of what is loaded and what is not, **there is no way to bypass this crash**

messages.content:
Speed Conservation Trick:
> If you release the control stick when surfacing from underwater swimming, you can slowly decelerate from your swimming speed at a rate of -10 speed units/frame (as opposed to snapping to 119.7 speed if your stick was not neutral). Optimally, the stick should only be released between 4-8 frames (depending on what part of the swim speed cycle you are at)

*(Currently theoretical)* Rareware GB's disappearing mechanic is partially based on camera location.
If your camera is far enough away (I used ScriptHawk to move during the Banana fairy camera cutscene, causing an extreme difference between camera and kong location), then it will not disappear. This may be chunk based (Camera in Chunk 0, kong in Chunk 1), this has yet to be fully investigated.

EDIT: If the camera is far enough away and facing a certain direction, it prevents the object being loaded. As such, the object will stop various processes (eg. Updating rotation) including pausing the execution of the object script that grabs kong location

messages.content:
Couple noteworthy things to do with successful fairy photos:
1) In order for a fairy to be successful, the fairy's referenced position (shown with the red dot) needs to be within the red box (amongst the other usual conditions like no walls inbetween you and the fairy if you're on N64). This is notably off-centre.

2) The fairy's position on the screen (what controls whether a photo is successful or not) that is referenced when determining whether the photo is successful or not is the position calculated from the previous frame. Therefore, with attempts to take a photo of an erratic fairy, it is better to lag *ever so slightly* behind the fairy's movement rather than otherwise as you are more likely to capture the fairies position **from the previous frame** than otherwise.

Upon entering K. Lumsy, if you get close to one of the torches closest to the entrance on the left or right hand side, and press this sequence of buttons:
> C-Up, D-Down
> C-Left, D-Right
> C-Down, D-Up
> C-Right, D-Left
A burping sound will play (One of the burps in the Xylophone game in Factory). This sets two global flags that are currently unknown in purpose.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zsfwg_ikJPU&ab_channel=Ballaam

**WARNING**
These two global flags have been set with Game.unlockMenus() inside ScriptHawk for a number of years, in which no-one has come across behaviour that would indicate that these flags serve any function in the final game. However, this hasn't been 101% confirmed yet, and could do something in the final game. **Since this code sets information that has the potential to stay permanently unlocked on the cart forever**, and the other dev code has been banned, there are a few things worth mentioning.
If you want to replicate this:
1) If you have an everdrive, you are fine to perform this on that since ED has ways to reset cart unlocks
2) If not, I would advise doing it on a cart/Wii U profile/emu that you can use gameshark codes on or one which you don't want to use for official speedrunning ever again
3) If you accidentally use it on your speedrunning cart/profile/emu, there are a couple ways you can revert your cart/profile/emu in the situation that it is found to do something and/or is banned from speedrunning categories:
> Use one of the following gameshark codes to reset the portion of the global flag block to a normal state:
```
US:  817ED55C 0700
PAL: 817ED47C 0700
JP: 817ED9CC 0700
```
> Perform a high-scoring rambi arena, and 1 frame after pressing A to confirm the final letter in your 3-letter name (after you get the high-score) turn off your console (window for this power down is around 0.1s on N64). **This will completely erase your permanent cart unlocks (in which you will need to re-acquire if you wish to have them again)**.

messages.content:
You can activate flashback warp using the Blast-o-Matic timer. Enter a bonus barrel, battle arena, or Snide/Funky or the like just after the timer runs out, and you will return to the main menu with a usable parent map value. "In Submap" only gets reset at the start of the game over fadeout, not at the end of it.

Unsurprisingly, this does not work with Hideout Helm barrels. It does work with the Helm battle arena, though. (press Z when the timer displays 0:02)
This cuts off about 13 minutes from the setup for Krusha Adventure. Any other trick or route relying on a flashback warp across files may also benefit from this.

<https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oWtczGbHwC4>

It's possible to perform an entire chain of flashback warps.

1. Set up a flashback warp in any location via any method (ISG, Helm timer, loading zone).
2. Enter and exit a map from BONUS (bonus barrels, battle arenas) or SHARED (Funky, Cranky, Snide, Candy, Troff 'n' Scoff). You will appear back where you set up the previous flashback warp.
3. Enter a "submap" of a level, which in this context means any map that isn't the main map of a level. (only the 7 main levels qualify)
(Side note: we may need to establish new terminology to distinguish submaps from bonus/shared maps)
4. If the submap is linked to any bonus/shared maps, enter and exit one of them.
For example, you could enter the tunnel or crypt in Creepy Castle and visit Candy, Funky, or Troff 'n' Scoff, or enter the bonus barrel in DK's barn in Fungi Forest.
When you leave the bonus/shared map, you will appear back where you entered the bonus/shared map in step 2.
5. Repeat steps 3 and 4 however many times you like.

Limitations: Every submap can only be used once in the chain. For example, if you've already entered Funky's store from the crypt, entering Funky or Troff 'n' Scoff from the crypt will not produce a new flashback warp.
Leaving a level via pause exit or the DK portal will reset flashback warp and thus break the chain. Same thing with returning to the start of a level (or to training grounds) by dying or voiding.

These are all the submaps I could find that contain links to bonus/shared maps:

**Angry Aztec**
Tiny's Temple
Llama Temple
Five Door Temple (Lanky)
Five Door Temple (Chunky)

**Gloomy Galleon**
Shipwreck (Diddy, Lanky, Chunky)
Shipwreck (DK, Tiny)
Shipwreck (Lanky, Tiny)
Submarine

**Fungi Forest**
DK's Barn
Mushroom Puzzle
Giant Mushroom
Barrel Blast

**Crystal Caves**
Rotating Room
Chunky's Cabin
Barrel Blast

**Creepy Castle**
Ballroom
Tower
Basement (DK, Diddy, Chunky)
Tunnel
Dungeon
Tree
Greenhouse
Crypt

When entering a submap (not bonus/shared), the game keeps track of where you entered from despite the fact that loading zones would suffice. The address used is the same as what we know as the parent map.
Entering multiple submaps and/or bonus/shared maps in a row will generate more and more parent map values. If the chain is broken, the game will start overwriting earlier parent maps.

Here is a chain of warps I did between Castle and Aztec:

87 - Castle main map
38 - Aztec main map
151 - Castle Tunnel
20 - Aztec Llama Temple
163 - Castle Dungeon
24 - Aztec 5 Door Temple (Chunky)
105 - Castle Tower
23 - Aztec 5 Door Temple (Lanky)
88 - Castle Ballroom

This provides a way to do 2 Batty Barrel Bandits in 2xA presses. 
1. Enter Snide's bonus barrel and activate flashback warp. (1xA)
2. Complete any bonus barrel that isn't in Galleon.
3. Grab Snide's GB.
4. Enter and exit Chunky's Galleon bonus barrel by failing the minigame. (1xA)
5. Complete any bonus barrel in a submap (again, not in Galleon).
6. Grab Chunky's GB.

I currently don't see any way to incorporate Factory Batty Barrel Bandit into the sequence. It is not located inside a submap, and even if we start out with it, we can't leave Factory without breaking the chain. Neither can we keep the chain going because Factory doesn't have any submaps with bonus/shared maps inside them. There might be some way I didn't think of, though.

You can fill up the list of parent maps just by entering and leaving submaps. If you attempt to generate parent map 18, the game freezes before the fadeout even starts.
This cannot happen in normal play because the two levels with the most maps are Caves (15) and Castle (15), discounting races, bosses, and lobbies.

On VC, it is possible to beat K. Rool without triggering the End Sequence.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aVAzVFjHSmY

Prepare a flashback warp to Castle lobby or Castle main, then go back to the main menu. MMM into a file that has only done Funky Weapons Glitch and visited Cranky in training grounds. Complete barrel barrel to get to Castle, then enter Troff 'n' Scoff from the tunnel or the crypt. Navigate past the void zones into the boss door to warp to K. Rool. After defeating K. Rool, Chunky will spawn in front of training grounds, which triggers the Isles escape cutscene and cancels the K. Rool defeated cutscene.

If you use Caves warp before this setup, you can buy Lanky's instrument to skip doing MMM later. You can then free kongs and buy the remaining moves in Castle without causing a flashback warp since Cranky and most T&S portals aren't in a submap.

This trick requires K. Rool Early because if you ever visit K. Lumsy, the Isles escape cutscene will play: <https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6QJrEJFr7Aw>

This was technically already possible because Caves warp can be used in conjunction with one flashback warp to Isles, so followup flashback warps aren't actually needed.

messages.content:
In the Spider Boss fight, when the big spider fires a pink projectile, you get put in a "trap bubble".
This sets a counter to 240, when you hit 0, you break free (unless you get hit by a miniSpider). What the developers *intended* you to do was to input the following stick sequence (All with at least 33% magnitude)
> Left, Up, Down, Right
Each correct stick input ticks the counter down 5

**However**, there is a super simple way to tick down by 5 every frame without spinning your stick like Mario Party player. If you hold Up-Left or Down-Right, it will break you out of the bubble within 48 frames (1.6s lagless). Up-Right and Down-Left do not tick the timer at all: https://youtu.be/nfR7Rlngb-k
If the kong is outside draw distance, the kong's stored positions become locked in a similar way to TBS: https://youtu.be/8qmWbDhlajs

embeds.title: Out of view Stored Position Lock
